e racial and colonial discourses of Imperial Germany. By positioning Zionist aspirations within a German colonial narrative, Altneuland presented Zionism as an extension, instead of a rejection, of German patriotism. By doing so, the journal's contributors hoped to recruit new supporters and model Zionism as a source of secular Jewish identity for German Jewry. While imagining future relationships between Jews, Arabs, and German settlers in Palestine, Oppenheimer and his contemporaries also reimagined the place of Jews among European nations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJewszGermanyxHistory. 0aSociologyzGermanyxHistory. 0aZionismzGermanyxHistory. 4aKolonialismus. 4aKosmopolitismus. 4aOppenheimer, Franz. 4aPalästina. 4aZionismus. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAnti-Semitism.  aColonialism.  aGermany.  aJewish identity.  aZionism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG0 cEPUBz97831107264800 cprintz978311072692340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110726435zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110726435zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110726435/original  a978-3-11-075070-6 DG Plus DeG Package 2021 